  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-1",
      "name": "Computing Careers",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do your skills and preferences align with computing careers and emerging technologies?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how their skills and interests align with computing careers and emerging technologies. Through collaborative activities, they analyze career personas, connect traits to career categories, and identify technologies that enhance career opportunities. At the end of the lesson, students reflect on their own traits and how they align with potential computing careers.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Career Exploration activity guide (one for each pair of students)\n- Ensure students have access to their Unit Guides (print copies or provide digital copies)",
        "student_overview": "**How do your skills and preferences align with computing careers and emerging technologies?**\n\nExplore how your skills and interests connect to exciting computing careers and technologies. Discover how emerging technologies solve real-world problems and reflect on the skills you have that align with your future goals."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-1",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-2",
      "name": "Computational Thinking",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can computational thinking help us simplify and solve complex problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, students activate prior knowledge about breaking tasks into smaller steps and practice computational thinking as a structured problem solving approach. They work in pairs to plan a school event (e.g., fundraiser, dance, talent show), applying computational thinking pillars (decomposition and abstraction) to solve the challenge. Students have an opportunity to use an AI Chatbot to help them complete the activity guide. During the wrap up, students reflect on the activity they completed and discuss the computational skills they practiced.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Planning a School Event activity guide (one for each pair of students)\n- (Optional) Gather several sticky notes for each student",
        "student_overview": "**How can computational thinking help us simplify and solve complex problems?**\n\nApply computational thinking principles —decomposition and abstraction — to plan a school event, and use an AI Chatbot for support."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-2",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-3",
      "name": "Designing Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we design algorithms to make decisions fairly and effectively?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the process of designing algorithms, breaking them into manageable steps, and visualizing them as flowcharts. They learn to incorporate sequencing, selection, and iteration into their algorithms and connect their work to real-world applications of AI, such as content moderation. Students also engage in peer feedback to refine their designs and reflect on ethical implications of algorithmic decision-making.",
        "preparation": "- Prepare sticky notes in two colors for each pair of students",
        "student_overview": "**How can we design algorithms to make decisions fairly and effectively?**\n\nLearn how to create and refine algorithms to solve real-world problems. Explore how algorithms make decisions using sequencing, selection, and iteration, and connect your learning to how AI moderates content."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-3",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-4",
      "name": "Variables and Data Flow",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do variables help us store and manage data in a program?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the concept of variables in Python. They classify data into four fundamental types: strings, integers, floats, and Booleans. Through unplugged and plugged examples, students practice using variables to store and update different data types. They have opportunities to predict and observe program outputs and reflect on how variables relate to real-world contexts.",
        "preparation": "- Print a set of data cards so that each pair of students can receive one complete set\n- Print copies of the My Variables activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do variables help us store and manage data in a program?**\n\nLearn to use variables in Python to store and update data of different types—strings, integers, floats, and Booleans—through hands-on activities and real-world examples."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-4",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-5",
      "name": "Working with Objects",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can objects be represented and controlled through programming?**\n\nThis lesson introduces students to objects in programming by exploring their attributes (descriptive properties) and methods (actions they can perform) through an unplugged activity and Python Lab. Students identify attributes and methods of everyday objects, connect these ideas to a `Painter` object in a grid-based Neighborhood environment, and practice writing pseudocode to navigate a maze. They then translate their pseudocode into Python, using the `Painter`’s methods like `move()`, `turn_left()`, and `paint(color)`. By the end of the lesson, students understand how attributes and methods control objects programmatically.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Grid Navigation activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can objects be represented and controlled through programming?**\n\nExplore how objects in programming have attributes and methods. Control a `Painter` object in the Neighborhood using pseudocode and Python to navigate and paint. By the end, see how programming creates precise instructions for movement and painting."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-5",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-6",
      "name": "Functions and Parameters",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can functions and parameters help us write cleaner, reusable code?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how functions and parameters simplify repetitive tasks and make code more readable and reusable. Students learn to define and call functions with parameters and reflect on the efficiency and clarity that functions bring to programming. Peer feedback is incorporated to improve their understanding and coding practices.",
        "preparation": "- Gather several sticky notes for each student",
        "student_overview": "**How can functions and parameters help us write cleaner, reusable code?**\n\nLearn how to create and use functions to simplify your programs. Discover how parameters can make your functions more flexible and reusable."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-6",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-7",
      "name": "Debugging Strategies",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What debugging strategies can you use to find and fix errors in your code?**\n\nThis lesson introduces debugging as an iterative process and equips students with four key debugging strategies: validation testing, code tracing & print statements, AI chatbot assistance, and error message clarifications. Through guided practice, students apply these strategies to identify and fix errors in their programs, developing problem-solving skills and confidence in debugging. The lesson concludes with a structured reflection, where students compare the effectiveness of different strategies and document their learning in their Unit Guides.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Debugging Strategies Handout (one per student)",
        "student_overview": "**What debugging strategies can you use to find and fix errors in your code?**\n\nDebugging is an iterative process used to find and fix errors in code. In this lesson, explore different debugging strategies, apply them to solve coding challenges, and reflect on which strategies are most effective."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-7",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-8",
      "name": "Introduction to Loops",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can you use while loops and functions together to repeat code efficiently?**\n\nIn this lesson, students dive into the concept of while loops in programming, learning how they help simplify repetitive tasks by executing code repeatedly while a condition is true. They explore the purpose and functionality of a while loop and learn how to write one to repeat actions, such as moving and painting, based on specific conditions. Students also discover how to use functions to encapsulate repetitive logic within while loops, making their code more efficient and reusable. Through hands-on practice, students will refine their ability to combine iteration and functions to solve real-world programming problems efficiently.",
        "student_overview": "**How can you use while loops and functions together to repeat code efficiently?**\n\nLearn how to use while loops to simplify repetitive tasks and practice combining them with functions to write efficient, reusable code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-8",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-9",
      "name": "Conditional Statements",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What role do conditional statements play in making decisions in your programs?**\n\nThis lesson introduces conditional statements as a way for programs to make decisions based on conditions. Students explore how `if` statements work, apply them using Painter methods, and analyze how conditionals affect program behavior. Through hands-on coding activities, students practice structuring conditionals and reflect on how conditions in programs impact fairness in real-world applications.",
        "student_overview": "**What role do conditional statements play in making decisions in your programs?**\n\nConditional statements help programs make decisions by checking if something is true before running certain code. In this lesson, practice using `if` statements to control movement and painting, and explore how conditionals are used in both coding and real-world decision-making."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-9",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-10",
      "name": "Algorithms IRL",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How might algorithms impact our daily lives?**\n\nThis lesson explores how algorithms make decisions in real-world applications and the ethical challenges that arise from those decisions. Students analyze and debug a flawed music recommendation algorithm, then examine the ethical trade-offs in autonomous vehicle decision-making. Through discussion and reflection, students consider how fairness, bias, and transparency impact trust in algorithmic systems.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Algorithm Decision-Making activity guide (one per pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**How might algorithms impact our daily lives?**\n\nAlgorithms make decisions in apps and technology, affecting everything from music recommendations to self-driving cars. In this lesson, explore how algorithms work, identify their limitations, and consider the ethical challenges of making fair and trustworthy decisions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-10",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-11",
      "name": "Decomposition",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What skills or characteristics helped you decompose your code to be more efficient today?**\n\nIn this lesson, students strengthen their understanding of decomposition by reflecting on past applications and working in small groups to break down a pixel image into functions using Python pseudocode. They then transition to coding their image through pair programming, testing, and debugging. The lesson concludes with a reflection on the importance of decomposition in solving complex problems efficiently.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Decomposing a Pixel Image activity guide (one per pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**What skills or characteristics helped you decompose your code to be more efficient today?**\n\nBreak down a pixel image into functions using pseudocode, then code it in Python. Reflect on how decomposition makes problem-solving more efficient."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-11",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-12",
      "name": "Two-Way and Nested Selection",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we make our programs more interactive?**\n\nIn this lesson, students use flowcharts and nested conditionals to model selection in programming. Students first create a flowchart to represent a decision process, such as staying at a party based on certain conditions. Then, students explore nested if/else statements by predicting, modifying, and debugging Python code that takes user input to control the Painter. The lesson concludes with a reflection on how user input and nested conditionals can make programs more interactive and dynamic.",
        "student_overview": "**How can we make our programs more interactive?**\n\nUse flowcharts and nested conditionals to model decision-making in programming. Then learn how to take user input to control how the Painter moves and paints."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-12",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-13",
      "name": "Pixels of Me Project",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I represent something about myself using programming and art?**\n\nIn this project, students design and code a pixel image that represents some aspect of them. They use computational thinking to break their design into subtasks, such as defining functions, coding loops, and using selection statements. They can use AI for brainstorming and debugging and then further refine their ideas through peer feedback and reflection. The project culminates in a gallery walk in which students show off their work.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Pixels of Me Project Planning Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I represent something about myself using programming and art?**\n\nUse Python to code a pixel image that represents. Apply your computational thinking skills to design, refine, and showcase your work."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-13",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pf-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    }
  ],
