  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "ade718bb-33f7-4ac1-9249-f3c66ce8e8f6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n\n- *What’s your favorite thing—an app, game, book, or something you use every day?*\n- *Who might work to create your favorite thing? What skills might they need?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight how computing skills and emerging technologies contribute to everyday tools and innovations students enjoy.*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be stuck. Ask questions like: *\"Do you have a favorite app or game you use every day?\" or \"What’s something you’ve enjoyed recently—like a book, movie, or a hobby?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Instruct students to jot down the first \"favorite thing\" that comes to mind. Then have students share their favorite thing with a neighbor. Have students work in pairs to brainstorm answers to who might work to create their favorite things and what skills those people would need."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ade718bb-33f7-4ac1-9249-f3c66ce8e8f6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9bce0e1d-e555-469f-aa9b-3271ed5c40a2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9bce0e1d-e555-469f-aa9b-3271ed5c40a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63386d52-9811-4500-bd12-4b9e21f5df9f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define **emerging technology** and explain some examples of emerging technologies, such as AI and Generative AI, robotics, the Internet of Things, Quantum Computing, augmented reality and virtual reality, and automation.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students are provided with a space to record important vocabulary in their Unit Guides. However, you might choose to also keep track of vocab words in a central place in the classroom, such as a Word Wall or Anchor Chart. See the Guide to Teaching Vocabulary to pick the instructional tool, resources, engagement and practice that works best for you and your students. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63386d52-9811-4500-bd12-4b9e21f5df9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d392da7-da91-4f1c-b5e3-37609c061ef2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d392da7-da91-4f1c-b5e3-37609c061ef2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03c8af32-9a4c-4287-bfae-69a13bf953c5",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some ways that emerging technologies might be involved with one of your favorite things?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight the connection between emerging technologies and real-world things that they use everyday. Guide students to see that technology plays a role in creating and improving everyday things that they already use. For example, if a student says they love TikTok, you could connect it to a person working in software development (creating the app) and using AI (personalized recommendations). If a student mentions books, you could connect how robotics or automation could be used to make and ship the books or computer vision could be used to take inventory. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allow students to take a minute to brainstorm with their partner some ways that emerging technologies might be involved in their favorite thing. Then facilitate a quick discussion, collecting a few examples and connecting them to a type of computing job or computing skills and emerging technologies. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03c8af32-9a4c-4287-bfae-69a13bf953c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5068592-7be8-4e36-9021-3dd8ff59a52b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5068592-7be8-4e36-9021-3dd8ff59a52b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac9f714f-e981-4e55-9850-9dfa70458579",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac9f714f-e981-4e55-9850-9dfa70458579",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1881a2e3-e4b5-4986-abbc-55662ab69888"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "445a98eb-8cee-4f50-b49f-d56d976ccaf2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Career Exploration activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before students start working, explain that careers can often be grouped based on the kind of work involved: working with People, working with Ideas, or working with Things. Explain to students that they'll use these categories throughout the activity to explore different computing careers and make connections to necessary skills and technologies.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the activity. Explain that students analyze a fictional persona’s social media to determine their interests and skills in order to match them to computing careers that might align with that persona’s skills and interests. For example, a persona might enjoy doing escape rooms which could mean they enjoy working with others or that they enjoy problem solving. Students then get help from a chatbot to brainstorm ways that emerging technologies could be used with that career.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1. \n- **Level 1:** Students choose one of the four personas and analyze the traits and match them to careers in Part 1 of their activity guide. \n- **Level 2:** Students use the information on the level to match their persona from Level 1 to a category, potential careers, and emerging technologies. \n- **Level 3:** Students use an AI Chatbot to explore more emerging technologies for their persona’s matched career. \n- **Level 4:** Students complete a Check for Understanding.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "Career Persona Exploration"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "445a98eb-8cee-4f50-b49f-d56d976ccaf2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "759efe30-e5df-44d5-8cfc-c9dde20d09be",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students struggling to make connections between skills/interests and potential careers. Ask students probing questions such as, \"What traits or skills stand out about this persona?\" or \"What careers involve working with people (ideas … things)?\" As you walk around the room, ensure students are using the activity guide to document the traits they notice about their persona and writing a justification for their skill/interest and career matches. Reassure students that there is no one “right” answer! For example, \"Maya might enjoy being an AI Engineer or a Game Developer because she’s creative, loves puzzles, and enjoys solving big challenges, and both AI Engineers and Game Developers use creativity and logic to build systems that solve complex problems.\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Part 1: If students struggle to match personas to careers, encourage them to focus on the skills and interests first. Ask questions like: \"What interests or skills does this persona have?\" Then, reference the Computing Careers Handout to find careers that align with those traits.\n- Part 2: If students are unsure how to connect emerging technologies to careers, provide examples. For instance: \"How might AI make a Data Scientist's job easier?\" or \"How could robotics help a Systems Architect design better solutions?\""
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Career Exploration Activity Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives.\n\nThe Check for Understanding on Level 4 can be used to formatively assess and provide feedback on students’ understanding of the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "759efe30-e5df-44d5-8cfc-c9dde20d09be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eb3fe4f4-36cc-4601-baa7-2f0adea42abe",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eb3fe4f4-36cc-4601-baa7-2f0adea42abe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c13f20f9-b85e-4c2d-88a3-dbda70382290",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Career Persona Self-Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will be using this every lesson throughout the unit. Determine if distributing physical copies of the Unit Guide or having students make their own digital copies will work best for you and your students."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c13f20f9-b85e-4c2d-88a3-dbda70382290",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0fe90c6-8910-46ea-9172-ba0ba679e2f0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0fe90c6-8910-46ea-9172-ba0ba679e2f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29d62b13-24a5-437d-9a31-d2a4609f41ef",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Self-Reflection Activity and explain that students will now reflect on their own skills and interests. Direct students to complete the Career Self-Reflection section on page one of their Unit Guide so that they can refer back to this self-reflection throughout the unit. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are highlighting or circling their top 3 self-identified skills or interests from the list. There is a spot for them to write in additional skills or interests that are not listed. If students do not identify with any of the listed skills or interests, encourage them to add ones that they do identify with. Encourage students to prompt the chatbot on Level 3 more than once to see if they get different suggestions and to only record those that they are most interested in. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- If students are struggling to identify their interests or skills, encourage them to think about hobbies, school projects, or favorite subjects. For example: \"If you enjoy drawing or designing, creativity might be one of your strengths.\"\n- If time permits, students could also ask the AI Career Chat Buddy what emerging tech might be used with the career(s) that interests them. Students can also flip the question around and ask the Chat Buddy what careers use the type of emerging tech that interests them the most."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Career Self-Reflection section in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29d62b13-24a5-437d-9a31-d2a4609f41ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58e74474-f68b-4b82-9d93-0c1b46f02353"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f505e06-1430-48b5-b415-7122f449070f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their Unit Guide before they share with a partner. If time allows, have students share with a second person not seated near them.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance: *\"Think about a skill or interest you rated yourself highly on earlier. How did it connect to one of the careers we explored?\"*",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, end the wrap-up with a whole-class share-out: Ask students if anyone would like to share a connection they made between their skills, a computing career, and an emerging technology? This can help reinforce key takeaways and provide inspiration for students who may have struggled."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f505e06-1430-48b5-b415-7122f449070f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c7fa1497-f7ff-463e-af63-5db449658220"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "45c96ba9-f41d-43d5-b5a4-1c5ef64749cc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What process do you take to clean up your room? How do you go about this task?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight the varied approaches that students suggest for accomplishing this common task. Point out any of the following if mentioned by students: the importance of breaking tasks into smaller steps (decomposition), the benefit of recognizing repeated steps (pattern recognition), the need to focus only on key information (abstraction).",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The discussion protocol Think-Pair-Share allows students time to independently reflect on a discussion question and get peer feedback before a class-wide discussion. Allow 1-2 minutes for students to write down bullet points or steps in their process. Then have students share what they wrote down with a partner (or in a group of three). As students are sharing out with a partner, circulate the classroom to find one or two students whose responses you want to highlight. Bring the class back together, and have these one or two students share their responses with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "45c96ba9-f41d-43d5-b5a4-1c5ef64749cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ada7c824-7c00-4cdb-bcc1-736a017bff74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d538474-ed00-44be-9648-d311941e0d16",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d538474-ed00-44be-9648-d311941e0d16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ada7c824-7c00-4cdb-bcc1-736a017bff74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "796c0378-99cb-40f7-8ba9-f15d3752db05",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "796c0378-99cb-40f7-8ba9-f15d3752db05",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ada7c824-7c00-4cdb-bcc1-736a017bff74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "58bde8ba-5e7d-4760-948c-81bad136af7d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *computational thinking*. Explain that computational thinking is like cooking a recipe:\n- You break down the recipe into steps – prepping ingredients, cooking, plating.\n- You notice similarities with other recipes you've made – chopping vegetables, boiling water.\n- You focus on essential steps and ignore unnecessary details – you don't need to know how the oven works, just how to set the temperature.\n- You follow or create a step-by-step process to cook the dish.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that computational thinking consists of four pillars: decomposition, pattern recognition, abstraction, and algorithm design. Emphasize that computational thinking isn't just for coding – these pillars are useful for solving all kinds of real-world problems.",
        "name": "School Event Planning Challenge",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This lesson will focus on decomposition and abstraction only, and pattern recognition and algorithm design will be discussed in greater depth in upcoming lessons, so don't spend too much time explaining all four of these pillars now."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "58bde8ba-5e7d-4760-948c-81bad136af7d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a58368a-2e53-420a-a466-c13ce957ac26",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a58368a-2e53-420a-a466-c13ce957ac26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dac6dbf3-57cb-4280-8da6-afb2a7ccf527",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *decomposition*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dac6dbf3-57cb-4280-8da6-afb2a7ccf527",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca571498-22bd-471d-bd8e-aaa39ac8dcd0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When you start a jigsaw puzzle, you don't try to put everything together at once. Instead, you break it down into smaller steps – first sorting edge pieces, then grouping by colors or patterns, and finally assembling sections before putting everything together.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca571498-22bd-471d-bd8e-aaa39ac8dcd0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a492865c-0832-4ac9-a9c4-40446055b7bc",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *abstraction*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a492865c-0832-4ac9-a9c4-40446055b7bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1acf22b-c52a-4ee8-91fa-3a7b9f310c2a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When you look at a map, you don't see every tree, building, or streetlight – only the important features like roads, landmarks, and distances. The map removes unnecessary details while keeping the essential information needed to navigate.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1acf22b-c52a-4ee8-91fa-3a7b9f310c2a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9bc39e11-cfe9-4011-9eb4-299fbaa9c9bd",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Planning a School Event activity guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Optionally, you can also give each pair a several sticky notes for them to write down their task ideas. This will make the process of refining their ideas easier than having to revise them directly on the activity guide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9bc39e11-cfe9-4011-9eb4-299fbaa9c9bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab008858-e428-41c0-8ddf-8b64181a2866",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab008858-e428-41c0-8ddf-8b64181a2866",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46987068-8704-4291-b527-a2ce90029ded",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students will work with their partner to plan a school event (e.g., fundraiser, dance, talent show). Allow students to either select from a provided list or come up with their own school or community-related event.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 2 Level 1. Students will use the AI chatbot to assist with completing the Decomposition section of the Planning a School Event activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46987068-8704-4291-b527-a2ce90029ded",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebe20111-860c-4221-b885-1d60574db423",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around and observe students as they work on their activity guide. Ask guiding questions like, \"What’s something you would need to buy for this type of event?\" and \"What types of tasks are similar to each other?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before students start filling out the activity guide, consider demonstrating how to use a chatbot level. Copy and paste one of the prompts from the activity guide into the first AI chatbot. Show students how they can customize the prompt to fit their needs and ask follow up questions to get the best responses. Encourage students to use the Tips at the bottom of the instruction panel. Demonstrate how to copy and paste one of the suggestions (e.g. \"Come up with 3 more ideas\") into the chat box after initiating a dialogue with the chatbot.\n\nStudents may have varying degrees of success with the example prompts, depending on the type of event they chose and the task they need clarified. Encourage students to customize these prompts to get the output they need. Highlight any pairs who have found particularly effective system prompts and encourage other students to use the same prompt template."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebe20111-860c-4221-b885-1d60574db423",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19a06d09-3009-48c2-808a-b0aafc59ae13",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19a06d09-3009-48c2-808a-b0aafc59ae13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37bbd37c-f736-4f4b-899f-e041906f81bb",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Once students have finished brainstorming their task list, have students pair up with another pair who chose the same (or a similar) event. Direct each pair to read through the other pair’s tasks before providing feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around and observe students as they give each other feedback. Ask guiding questions like, \"What tasks might you want to add to your own list\" and \"What tasks should be broken up into separate tasks?\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did breaking the event into smaller tasks make it easier to plan?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to articulate that planning the event became easier because they were able to see all of the tasks that they would need to accomplish.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2 and Level 3. \n- **Level 2**: Students will use the AI chatbot to assist with completing the Abstraction section of the Planning a School Event activity guide.\n- **Level 3:** Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Planning a School Event activity guide and the Check For Understanding question on Level 3 can be used as formative assessments of the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37bbd37c-f736-4f4b-899f-e041906f81bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "33354a8d-1011-4cd1-8fc9-15ea9f510883",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "33354a8d-1011-4cd1-8fc9-15ea9f510883",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66e0a815-5182-4f72-bb77-a0437a97dfd1",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did abstraction help simplify your plan?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to articulate that abstraction helped them eliminate unnecessary details and see the big picture of what tasks they would need to complete.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can you use the skills of decomposition and abstraction in the real world?*\n- Use the Raise a Righteous Hand protocol to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students make connections to ways they might already be using decomposition and abstraction in the real world. Figuring out which classes have assigned homework due the next day is an example of decomposition. Using the internet is an example of abstraction, since you don’t need to know exactly how it works in order to use it. See if students can make connections to ways engineers might use decomposition and abstraction in their jobs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66e0a815-5182-4f72-bb77-a0437a97dfd1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eeaf8db5-b0fe-4edd-ab08-d1bf0b375ec3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "47b22574-040b-4630-b2cf-e112b23824f5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance. Have them think back to the Warm Up question “*What process do you take to clean up your room? How do you go about this task?*” Have students consider how decomposition and abstraction help solve this task. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the unit guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "47b22574-040b-4630-b2cf-e112b23824f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "76f7e14a-5b29-4f1c-8184-9f7340ff1db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db8819bf-2f03-466f-bef8-b79ddfab1756",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db8819bf-2f03-466f-bef8-b79ddfab1756",
        "lesson_activity.key": "76f7e14a-5b29-4f1c-8184-9f7340ff1db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e17cd3af-67f9-449c-b2f0-af8d32ba60cc",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the Round Robin protocol. Guide students through the process of getting into small groups and designating who will share first."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e17cd3af-67f9-449c-b2f0-af8d32ba60cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "76f7e14a-5b29-4f1c-8184-9f7340ff1db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37339893-7089-46df-9efb-f49d09d425d9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to answer the warm-up question."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37339893-7089-46df-9efb-f49d09d425d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9bba05a-0dc8-460e-8e5f-a4af578a3e11",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might need help getting started. Ask: *\"What’s the first thing you’d do to if you wanted to create playlists for different events?\" or \"What categories might help organize the playlist?\"* Encourage students to think about the order of actions and any decisions they would need to make along the way.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display students’ anonymous responses for the class. Use their answers to lead the class in a discussion about what steps were identified and what decisions were made. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students do not need to have firm ideas for how to break a problem down into these steps - that’s what they will explore today. The goal of the playlist scenario is to give students the opportunity to begin thinking about breaking down a problem into smaller steps."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9bba05a-0dc8-460e-8e5f-a4af578a3e11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fb61af7-c969-4913-b088-9a53ac9d1dc6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fb61af7-c969-4913-b088-9a53ac9d1dc6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41c64f42-64a6-4cec-b91e-2c3ecc5ad191",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you notice?*\n- *What do you wonder?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share what they notice and wonder about the responses. Look for student responses that break down the problem into steps and responses that identify decisions points to help drive the discussion towards the idea of an algorithm.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Highlight any student responses that involve doing things in a certain order, any steps that happened more than once, or decisions they would need to make, such as sorting songs into groups based on their energy or mood. Point out any of those concepts in their steps and connect them to the idea of an algorithm - a step-by-step process that often involves steps in certain order (sequencing), decision-making (selection), and repetition (iteration)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41c64f42-64a6-4cec-b91e-2c3ecc5ad191",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7dc16959-9de7-462d-a456-65ba94949a2e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7dc16959-9de7-462d-a456-65ba94949a2e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "508a7e0c-e11f-40cc-a235-d3bb0166b8a7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that an algorithm is a set of step-by-step instructions to solve a problem. Algorithms often include sequencing (steps in order), selection (making decisions), and iteration (repeating steps). \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to add the vocabulary term to their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out the fact that in identifying some steps and decisions in creating a playlist, they dipped their toes into creating a “Playlist” algorithm. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "508a7e0c-e11f-40cc-a235-d3bb0166b8a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5b895ecc-4d49-4c2d-bc9c-77e191b01438",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5b895ecc-4d49-4c2d-bc9c-77e191b01438",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e7eb2dc-26ea-4280-9b13-a66421b5ffff",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e7eb2dc-26ea-4280-9b13-a66421b5ffff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29e87926-9f43-4d58-9252-7b26801dc499"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "83a2da22-c7c5-4497-9138-192e3587e00a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the steps for designing an algorithm. Explain that we follow these steps to make the process structured and logical. ",
        "name": "Designing an Algorithm",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, you can engage students with a quick recall discussion and ask the following questions:\n- Why is it important to decompose a complex problem or break it into smaller steps?\n- How does decomposition help with creating an algorithm?\n- Reinforce that following these steps ensures clarity and helps avoid mistakes in problem-solving."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "83a2da22-c7c5-4497-9138-192e3587e00a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6694c6e4-27ed-4038-aacf-291cb7c50f00",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6694c6e4-27ed-4038-aacf-291cb7c50f00",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a3153eb-7ecf-45fa-a894-c0806d22f027",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a few minutes to turn and talk to their elbow partner and discuss how they would go through the first three steps to decide what to wear. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- It is okay if students don’t come up with every single step and decision point - as long as students have identified a couple steps and at least one or two decisions you can move on to start sharing\n- If students struggle to understand the point of the first step, encourage them to think about how the steps build on each other. For example, \"Understanding the problem helps you identify what decisions need to be made and how to plan the steps.\"\n- If students struggle to get started, provide a guiding question: \"What might be the first step you take before deciding what to wear?\"\n- Look for groups that identify specific decision points (e.g., \"check the weather\") and try to use those as examples in the upcoming share-out."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a3153eb-7ecf-45fa-a894-c0806d22f027",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70c655c2-9b33-4302-b28a-abd4de293de9",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70c655c2-9b33-4302-b28a-abd4de293de9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fc74ef4b-6ff1-4f86-8bee-93bcbc05ab51",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the information on the slide to explain to students the \"Shout Out, Share Out\" protocol. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. Record students' responses on the board, and note any common answers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a moment and look at what was shared together. Point out any similarities from each step. Highlight the different decisions students mentioned and connect them to how we approach problem-solving. Click through the animated slide to explain that everyday decisions, like deciding what to wear, can be broken into simple steps. Algorithms help us solve more complex problems by organizing tasks and guiding decision-making efficiently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Go over the final step of designing an algorithm: organizing steps and decisions into a logical sequence using a flowchart. Point out how the flowchart visually connects actions and decisions to guide the process.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a handful of two different color sticky notes. Students will also need some space near their computers to arrange their sticky notes into a flowchart.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your classroom setup doesn’t allow for students to easily work on the computer while using sticky notes to create flowcharts at their desk, consider using the optional activity guide instead and distributing copies to students when you distribute sticky notes. The optional activity guide has all of the same options for students to choose from as the options in Level 2. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fc74ef4b-6ff1-4f86-8bee-93bcbc05ab51",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81401a3b-7f8a-4add-833a-02534153305c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81401a3b-7f8a-4add-833a-02534153305c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70ec4237-ade1-4761-a80d-9735280da772",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that their task is to design an algorithm using the algorithm design steps. Let students know that they will use sticky notes for their steps and decisions points - one color for the steps or processes and one color for decision points.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Levels 2 through 6 to pick one of the scenarios to work with and design an algorithm for. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70ec4237-ade1-4761-a80d-9735280da772",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68c3dc2f-7696-4026-b65a-87d3306793b4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are clearly identifying steps and decision points in their algorithms. Ask questions like: \"What is the goal of your algorithm?\" or \"Does your flowchart account for all possible outcomes?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Ensure students are using sticky notes for steps (processes) and decision points in order to make rearranging steps easier.\n- Encourage students to start simple and add details later if they feel stuck. For example, “Start with the first major step. What needs to happen first? What’s the next logical step?”\n- If students struggle with decision points, guide them by asking: “What question would your algorithm need to answer to move forward?”"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The responses in Levels 2 through 6 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68c3dc2f-7696-4026-b65a-87d3306793b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75303fa2-2d25-45b7-82fd-a3a7cab4f813",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75303fa2-2d25-45b7-82fd-a3a7cab4f813",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fea4bfb7-82bb-4134-910e-b5dc2f39d344",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to pair up with another group to share their flowcharts, use the questions on the slide to provide constructive feedback, and then revise their flowcharts based on that feedback. Emphasize that the goal is to make their algorithms clearer and more complete.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are giving meaningful feedback and incorporating it into their revisions. Ask questions like: *\"What feedback are you using to improve your flowchart?\"* or *\"How does your revision address missing steps or outcomes?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you wish to collect students’ algorithm flowcharts, you can have students attach their finished flowchart sticky notes to a poster and display everyone’s flowcharts. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fea4bfb7-82bb-4134-910e-b5dc2f39d344",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "31ffadbd-89a1-47f0-aa29-2654a4bd11f4",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "31ffadbd-89a1-47f0-aa29-2654a4bd11f4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0ec938b-f23d-4652-8d02-ad4ab8b988ad",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to answer the Check for Understanding questions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The responses in Level 7 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0ec938b-f23d-4652-8d02-ad4ab8b988ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e0a3e656-6d5b-4e78-b4c2-ec8b858aad88",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e0a3e656-6d5b-4e78-b4c2-ec8b858aad88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe6fdd25-d0e7-448c-9a83-e40e62402280",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What challenges did you face when deciding what to keep, delete, or highlight?*\n- *How might AI handle similar challenges?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students reflect on the challenges they faced when designing their algorithms, such as balancing fairness or handling multiple outcomes. Encourage them to connect these challenges to how AI might tackle similar problems, highlighting both its strengths (e.g., efficiency) and limitations (e.g., bias or lack of context). The goal is for students to recognize the importance of thoughtful algorithm design in addressing complex, real-world issues.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a deep topic and could spark a lot of discussion. Unless you have the additional time to devote to this discussion, try to keep discussion concise to stay with a 5 minute timeframe. Ensure students that the topics of societal impact and using AI ethically will be revisited. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe6fdd25-d0e7-448c-9a83-e40e62402280",
        "lesson_activity.key": "160cf7e4-a0ad-45ca-ad9b-628e18651e31"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebfca311-b1d7-408a-97b2-a98ed1b1c11c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to write their responses in their Unit Guide. After two or three minutes, facilitate a quick sharing activity (e.g., Whip Around or Popcorn Share), calling on a few students to share their ideas.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebfca311-b1d7-408a-97b2-a98ed1b1c11c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f769f22-9644-497b-a761-61834e25fa13"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d3cdde2-9bc8-4b41-a0e0-251d637368e6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a full set of data cards (16 cards in total).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students to sort their cards into groups of their choice. Make sure they discuss with their partner their rationale for choosing how to group the cards.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students to sort the cards into four categories: strings, integers, floats, and Booleans. After they finish sorting the piles, have them complete the definitions for these words in their Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Compare your sorted cards with another group. Are there any differences in how you categorized the cards? Did you have to make any changes from how you originally sorted your cards?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to compare their decisions for how to categorize the cards with the decisions made by another group. Students should be able to justify their choices for how they sorted the cards.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Can you identify one of each data type about yourself or someone you know?*\n- Use the Raise a Righteous Hand protocol to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to distinguish between the four fundamental data types: strings, integers, floats, and Booleans. This discussion will prepare them to complete the Variable Data Types activity guide. You can turn this discussion into a game by having students think of data types about celebrities and have other students try to identify them by their information. For example, nickname = “The GOAT”, olympic_medals = 7, height = 4.66, gymnast = True would represent Simone Biles.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The protocol \"Raise a Righteous Hand\" involves students raising their hands to volunteer information, share experiences, or answer questions based on their unique knowledge or personal experiences. The term \"righteous\" in this context is used to emphasize the value and importance of the information being shared. It suggests that the contributions are genuine, meaningful, and worthy of attention and respect."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d3cdde2-9bc8-4b41-a0e0-251d637368e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "53361180-aafd-4589-b012-d3a2b124a72d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19b8a679-bbb9-4b0a-8dc5-34ca7a4905d4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19b8a679-bbb9-4b0a-8dc5-34ca7a4905d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "53361180-aafd-4589-b012-d3a2b124a72d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "534da86e-096a-4b35-984f-25aa75c9cc2f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *variable*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "534da86e-096a-4b35-984f-25aa75c9cc2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "53361180-aafd-4589-b012-d3a2b124a72d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ee136d7-f521-4b09-afa3-2bc5b0044e1e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the My Variables activity guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that each student will choose a hobby or activity they enjoy, such as skateboarding. They will have to fill out the chart with a variable of each data type: string, integer, float, and boolean. Each variable should be given a name and a value. Then have students brainstorm how this value might change over time and write their answer in the last column.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "My Variables",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a good time to prepare students for writing variables in Python. In Python, variables are written using “snake case” where individual words are_separated_like_this using an underscore “_”. Have students write their variable names in snake case in their activity guide. Some examples are provided above, e.g. “favorite_trick”."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The My Variables activity guide can be collected and used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ee136d7-f521-4b09-afa3-2bc5b0044e1e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c88e96b3-cce6-4fbb-9ff2-29ab11730cae",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c88e96b3-cce6-4fbb-9ff2-29ab11730cae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bcd6cbe-5455-46bf-99a5-3d73c9fd8494",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might these variables change over time?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that variables store information that can be updated as needed. Help students who are stuck by asking: \"Would your number of skateboards change over time?\" or \"Would your boolean variable change as your skill level increases?\" or \"Perhaps your favorite trick changes?\" Instruct students to jot down how each variable might change or evolve over time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to complete the fourth column of their activity guide \"How might it change over time?\" if they have not yet done so."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bcd6cbe-5455-46bf-99a5-3d73c9fd8494",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b5d1b42-4805-4919-a61f-8cfcb4967ca4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that this is what coding levels will look like on the Code.org platform. Lines 1 and 2 are part of the user's program. Console is where the print out will appear. Ask students to predict what will appear in console when the user clicks \"Run\".\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be stuck. Ask questions like: *“What data types are being used in this program?”\n- *“What might happen when we combine strings using `+`?”*\n- *“What data types are being used in this program?”*",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Unplugged Predict and Run",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allowing students to look at the code in pairs can help them synthesize what they are learning by articulating their thoughts to each other, and hearing multiple perspectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b5d1b42-4805-4919-a61f-8cfcb4967ca4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bfcb8e3a-e3ec-47db-add9-2210218d8d1f",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bfcb8e3a-e3ec-47db-add9-2210218d8d1f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70687f9e-b22b-4509-a41d-1ae975910655",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share if the output was what they expected, then explain that the reason the program doesn't print out \"name loves pizza\" is because **name** is a variable that stores the string \"Rylee\". Click through the animated slide to explain the following:\n- A *variable* is a named storage location in memory that can hold data and be changed during program execution. Students can think of it as a container that holds data. They can use variables to store different types of information, such as numbers, strings, lists, and more.\n- Assignment operators like = update values of variables. Other assignment operators include += and -=\n- Arithmetic operators like +, -, x, ÷ perform mathematical calculations on numbers. For example, + adds values together. Using the + sign can also be a way to combine text. This is called string concatenation.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask students to predict what will appear in console when the user clicks \"Run\".\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** If students are struggling, ask the following questions to help them think about the code: *\"What data types are being used in this program?\" \"What might happen this time when we combine integers using +?\" \"How does updating num_pets change the output?\"*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share if the output was what they expected.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to learn how to use Python Lab.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Investigate and Modify",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students might be curious what `str()` means in this context. You can let them know that they will explore this concept more in later levels. If you want to explain to them how it works, have them articulate the difference between the `num_pets` variable which is an integer and the `print` statement `\"Number of pets:\"` which is a string. In order to cast an integer to print out as a string, students will need to add `str()`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70687f9e-b22b-4509-a41d-1ae975910655",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6aecf496-d260-4478-bdc9-fd05daaf87da",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6aecf496-d260-4478-bdc9-fd05daaf87da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b61912ca-715b-417e-9b09-d61d58cec3e7",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 2 to complete Levels 2 through 5.\n- **Level 2:** Students update the values stored in string variables.\n- **Level 3:** Students create a Boolean variable and print it out.\n- **Level 4:** Students modify an integer value stored in a variable.\n- **Level 5:** Students answer a Check for Understanding question."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b61912ca-715b-417e-9b09-d61d58cec3e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8f9f09a-70b0-4276-b7fd-333afd3c41d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2516c2e1-3584-4a1f-86a5-c2ac979ada20",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete level 5 will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objective:\n- Create and modify variables in Python to store and update different types of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
