    {
      "key": "4a6d7ba9-8c18-4f98-8ee4-4b42ad159682",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a6d7ba9-8c18-4f98-8ee4-4b42ad159682",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6cdb96a4-a6d3-49eb-a9ee-08bf2473d8b5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8195be75-0580-4898-9fb2-3e5090b83f6e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Grid Navigation activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that just like the objects examined in the warm up have characteristics and actions, they're going to be working with objects that have characteristics and actions. Beginning with navigating an object to represent the Painter, to points around a grid. Have students follow the instructions on their activity guide to write pseudocode to navigate the painter from point A to the various endpoints on the grid. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for students to be breaking the problem into clear, sequential steps (e.g., \"move forward,\" \"turn left\").",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Maze Navigation with the Painter",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If this is the first time your students are using pseudocode explain that pseudocode is a simple way to plan out your code before you write it in a programming language. It’s like writing instructions in plain English (or another natural language) instead of Python or other coding languages.\n\nThe purpose of pseudocode is to help you focus on solving the problem and organizing your ideas without worrying about the exact syntax. It’s a great tool for learning because it helps you think logically and break down problems into smaller steps, just like a programmer does."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8195be75-0580-4898-9fb2-3e5090b83f6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2fa7d26-dca3-4051-8a8b-3f6f5de526ae",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2fa7d26-dca3-4051-8a8b-3f6f5de526ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2c539974-4746-4af5-b371-c1cb10046a90",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the reflection questions in the activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2c539974-4746-4af5-b371-c1cb10046a90",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f6bc788-9c46-44d3-9d37-62b6c4f271d5",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *object*. Explain in Python, an object is an instance of a class. It is something you can describe and use. We will be coding the Painter object.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *class*. Explain that a class is like a blueprint that defines all of the possible methods and characteristics. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction to The Neighborhood",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "While understanding classes is a key part of Python, this unit is designed as an introduction and will not dive into the details of what a class is. Instead, the focus will be on using objects and methods with dot notation to build a foundational understanding. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f6bc788-9c46-44d3-9d37-62b6c4f271d5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "94359701-5ff2-4d17-b765-427414b1b0be",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "94359701-5ff2-4d17-b765-427414b1b0be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35232004-def2-4cc3-95b0-7501376a67e3",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *attribute*. Explain that In Python, attributes are descriptions or information about an object like location or direction.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *method*. Explain that in Python, methods are actions the object can do like move, turn left, or paint.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *dot notation*. Explain that in Python, we use dot notation to instruct an object. Dot notation involves writing the object’s name, followed by a dot, and then the attribute or method you want to access."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35232004-def2-4cc3-95b0-7501376a67e3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1315975e-1265-4274-a801-229566b48f73",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 1 to learn about the The Neighborhood and the `Painter`.\n- **Level 1:** Students read through information in the panels\n- **Level 2:** Students explore the main.py and painter.py files",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Python Lab"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1315975e-1265-4274-a801-229566b48f73",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dfb4ba71-6c2d-4d9c-bb1d-8038c11b89d2",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the answers to the discussion questions in Level 2 so that students understand the `Painter` object’s default attributes. Explain each time we add a Painter object it is placed at x = 0, y = 0 and it is facing east. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ensure students understand that since they will not need to see the `painter.py` class moving forward, it will be hidden in Python Lab. They will still be able to access its methods as long as they include the `from neighborhood import Painter` line of code."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dfb4ba71-6c2d-4d9c-bb1d-8038c11b89d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8509f60-fa10-41eb-87b8-39f1e4e45dd3",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8509f60-fa10-41eb-87b8-39f1e4e45dd3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b6d3fc1a-a555-49f3-b6f5-2f67b1bf169c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Transition:** Direct students to complete Levels 3 and 4.\n- **Level 3:** Students add a `Painter` object and four `painter.move()` methods.\n- **Level 4:** Students run the code and discuss the purpose of the paint can. Then they uncomment all of the commented code to observe how the `Painter` takes the paint from the paint can and then paints one square at a time."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b6d3fc1a-a555-49f3-b6f5-2f67b1bf169c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5073ea3e-2c77-4b1b-a67a-68fc6850f284",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Support students' transition from planning to coding while fostering independence and problem-solving skills by asking guiding questions when they get stuck.\n- \"What does your pseudocode say should happen next?\"\n- \"Python is picky about spaces and spelling—double-check your line.\"\n- Encourage debugging: \"What part of your code is working? What part isn't? How can you figure out why?\"\n- Highlight different strategies: \"I like how you broke down this turn step.\"\n- Suggest partnerships: \"Check with your partner.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5073ea3e-2c77-4b1b-a67a-68fc6850f284",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3337ff36-1ff4-430e-a115-5b388a908701",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3337ff36-1ff4-430e-a115-5b388a908701",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9594264-24d0-4577-afd4-2a876f05e6c4",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before the whip around, prompt students to share what they discovered about the following aspects:\n- The `Painter`'s default attributes (xLocation = 0, yLocation = 0, direction = east, paint = 0)\n- Using dot notation \n- Turning right\n- Taking paint and painting \n\nImportant reminders:\n- Include the underscore when using `turn_left()`\n- Use single or double quotes to specify paint color\n- The `Painter` must take paint before they can paint any square\n- The number on the paint bucket refers to the number of square the painter will be able to paint"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9594264-24d0-4577-afd4-2a876f05e6c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
