      }
    },
    {
      "key": "23cd3543-10ec-4ef9-91cb-fcadb1708a3e",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete level 5 will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objective:\n- Translate pseudocode into Python code using sequence and defined methods.\n- Write and test pseudocode to control an object"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "23cd3543-10ec-4ef9-91cb-fcadb1708a3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6f88122a-882a-41d1-b0d7-89a2d382a48b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5dec0ec1-ba6c-4447-a687-7424c6ea28ca",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance: *\"Attributes describe the details of the object, and methods let it perform actions, so together they define what the object is and what it can do.”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5dec0ec1-ba6c-4447-a687-7424c6ea28ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ac0abd4-dc11-4ce6-a758-87dcfa32cd01"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7bfd841f-00b5-46c7-a96d-c54d660f199c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7bfd841f-00b5-46c7-a96d-c54d660f199c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ac0abd4-dc11-4ce6-a758-87dcfa32cd01"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b16b30eb-b8be-4c7e-95b0-c2b71a479e05",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students turn to Lesson 2 in their Unit Guide to review their identified skills and interests. Then have them consider which they used in today’s lesson with specific evidence. Suggest using a sticky note or other temporary method if it helps to jot their ideas down prior to sharing with a partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students turn to a partner to share their reflection."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b16b30eb-b8be-4c7e-95b0-c2b71a479e05",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ac0abd4-dc11-4ce6-a758-87dcfa32cd01"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eefe42e4-700e-4e64-a419-53b9c7275430",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What `Painter` class method do you wish you had last class that would’ve made things easier?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify `Painter` methods that would have made their `Painter` tasks easier, most notably, a `turn_right()` method. The goal is to get students to recognize repetitive tasks in the previous lesson and think about how having a `Painter` method for it would have simplified their programming tasks. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to come up with an answer, ask them questions like, *“What tasks did you find yourself repeating over and over?”* or *“What steps were the most frustrating or time-consuming?”* or *If you could create a new `Painter` method, what would it do?”*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eefe42e4-700e-4e64-a419-53b9c7275430",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc886bd2-def8-4ab4-954a-55b3cf6d21f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "701eb0d8-d090-4109-89e7-86f548fb2c39",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "701eb0d8-d090-4109-89e7-86f548fb2c39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc886bd2-def8-4ab4-954a-55b3cf6d21f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2d084ae-4121-4e82-9e61-b6805a8ac657",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Think back to last class. How did you make the `Painter` turn right when you only had `painter.turn_left()` available?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should reflect on how they solved the limitation of only having `painter.turn_left()` in the last class by calling the `turn_left()` method three times in a row. The goal is for students to recognize this as a repetitive task that could be simplified with a function, such as `turn_right()`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2d084ae-4121-4e82-9e61-b6805a8ac657",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc886bd2-def8-4ab4-954a-55b3cf6d21f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f83c7af2-f38b-4cc6-adb6-656d852efa02",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1 to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check if students predict that the program will move the painter 3 times, paint blue and then move forward 3 times again. If students are stuck, ask guiding questions like, \"What’s happening inside the `move_fast()` function?\" Or \"How is this different from the `Painter` methods you’ve used before?\" ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allowing students to look at the code in pairs can help them synthesize what they are learning by articulating their thoughts to each other, and hearing multiple perspectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f83c7af2-f38b-4cc6-adb6-656d852efa02",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "334cb584-d6a4-4c8a-8537-4412ca0e2cec",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "334cb584-d6a4-4c8a-8537-4412ca0e2cec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9e8313d-0bd8-45f3-b348-4f740998f6dc",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about the code in this program? What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal of this discussion is to ensure students notice the syntax used to define a function and the function call. Student should also notice that the `move_fast()` function call does **not **use dot notation like the `Painter` class methods they have been using, like `painter.move()` or `painter.paint(“blue”)`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9e8313d-0bd8-45f3-b348-4f740998f6dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "106b898d-7034-4603-9e6c-cf3f62e5a4be",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that `Painter` class methods are defined in the `Painter` class and use dot notation.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *function*. Explain how a key benefit of creating a function is that they make our code more reusable and organized. For example, instead of repeatedly using `painter.turn_left()` three times to turn right, they defined and reused their own `turn_right()` function.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that user-defined functions are created by programmers themselves and therefore not associated with a class, so they do not use dot notation.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Investigate and Modify",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to understand the difference, you can provide additional explanation:\n- Dot notation is used for `Painter` class methods associated with *attributes* and *behaviors* of an object.\n- `Painter` class methods like `painter.move()` use dot notation because they’re tied to the `Painter` object, while student-created functions like `move_fast()` don’t use dot notation because they’re independent, and not created or associated with a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "106b898d-7034-4603-9e6c-cf3f62e5a4be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2e4e9488-0c13-45af-a2d1-750b3148fd1b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2e4e9488-0c13-45af-a2d1-750b3148fd1b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a315f367-94bf-47c2-9631-3d1fc5d5fc9f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that when we define functions that we know we will want to reuse, we can save them in a separate file (`custom.py`) instead of rewriting them every time. In Python Lab, we can import `custom.py` as a separate file and use its functions inside `main.py`. This helps keep our code organized and allows us to reuse functions we’ve already written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i>** Do This:** Point out that the function in `custom.py` uses a parameter (`painter`), meaning it can work with different objects. When calling the function in `main.py`, we pass in an actual object (e.g., `bob`). This allows us to reuse the same function for multiple objects without rewriting it.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that when we import `custom.py` into Python Lab, we can call its functions inside `main.py` using dot notation. For example, `custom.turn_right(bob)` tells Python that the `turn_right` function is located in `custom.py` and should be used with the object `bob`. Without dot notation, Python wouldn't know where to find `turn_right`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Transition:** Direct students to complete Levels 2 through 5.\n- **Level 2:** Students create and test a `turn_right()` function.\n- **Level 3:** Students create and test a `turn_around()` function.\n- **Level 4:** Students refactor repeated code into a `paint_line(color)` function.\n- **Level 5:** Students answer a Check for Understanding question."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a315f367-94bf-47c2-9631-3d1fc5d5fc9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4f988b61-96d6-4366-a197-bc50c90d1894",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete level 5 will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objective:\n- Differentiate between parameters and arguments in a function."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4f988b61-96d6-4366-a197-bc50c90d1894",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19da9c8d-86ea-4c59-9cc1-5ebcd3e19990",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19da9c8d-86ea-4c59-9cc1-5ebcd3e19990",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1b53f85d-5920-4707-bbb2-d8200f1f0009",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The protocol \"Raise a Righteous Hand\" involves students raising their hands to volunteer information, share experiences, or answer questions based on their unique knowledge or personal experiences. The term \"righteous\" in this context is used to emphasize the value and importance of the information being shared. It suggests that the contributions are genuine, meaningful, and worthy of attention and respect.\n\nPrompt students to share what they discovered about the following aspects:\n- Creating a function\n- Calling a function\n- Parameters\n- Comments"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1b53f85d-5920-4707-bbb2-d8200f1f0009",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f486c9a-32a6-4ef2-b8be-38246c1ff0bb",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f486c9a-32a6-4ef2-b8be-38246c1ff0bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8b4c9e7-4464-4686-a379-9ebd7ff4850b",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the syntax of defining a function and calling a function and the required indentation for the code within the function definition as they add the information to their unit guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *parameter*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *argument*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, you can give students a quick check for understanding prompt by asking them to identify which line of code they would need to update if we wanted to paint with pink instead of blue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8b4c9e7-4464-4686-a379-9ebd7ff4850b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9cd21f0a-35b1-4385-87bd-53abf7d3e71e",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9cd21f0a-35b1-4385-87bd-53abf7d3e71e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e018e36e-743b-4185-a72f-35db4ce99b51",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *comment* and explain what they are used for:\n- Explain code’s purpose by describing what the code is meant to do.\n- Improve readability by making your code easier for others (and yourself) to understand later.\n- Support collaboration by allowing team members to quickly understand your code.\nAll of which aid in debugging code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the TAG feedback protocol and explain to students that they will be using this TAG protocol to give and receive feedback on the first practice level 6. Ensure students have a sticky note to write their TAG feedback on for a classmate.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 6 to complete Levels 6 through 7.\n- **Level 6:** Students practice combining functions to create a unique pattern and will give TAG feedback to a peer.\n- **Level 7:** Students choose a Neighborhood layout and write a program using the functions they’ve created to complete a task efficiently",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete these levels will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objectives:\n- Define and call functions to simplify repetitive tasks\n- Define functions with parameters to make code reusable and flexible.\n- Differentiate between parameters and arguments in a function\n- Writing descriptive comments to explain the purpose of your functions and code segments"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e018e36e-743b-4185-a72f-35db4ce99b51",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32601a92-9592-4acb-96ce-707aa2715c4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec31434b-3ef3-47fd-967f-480656ff41b1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to share their thoughts on the Question of the Day with their small group before adding their own responses to their Unit Guides.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Answers to the question of the day can be used to formatively asses the following lesson objectives:\n- Define and call functions to simplify repetitive tasks\n- Define functions with parameters to make code reusable and flexible.\n\nLook for student answers to include how functions reduce repetition by grouping tasks into reusable code blocks and how parameters make functions flexible by allowing different inputs, such as using one function to paint multiple colors. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec31434b-3ef3-47fd-967f-480656ff41b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1122139a-2eec-42e1-9e72-a95218efcd7e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "07fa57ac-06b4-4672-b6b2-dc2cc8b14be5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do you do when something doesn’t work the way you expect?*\n- *How do you overcome frustration while solving problems?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should conclude that problem-solving often involves trying multiple strategies to overcome challenges and that these strategies are part of a systematic process. Student responses might include taking breaks, asking for help, breaking the task into smaller steps, or trying different things. By the end of the discussion, students should recognize that these approaches relate directly to debugging in programming.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for strategies students already use, such as taking breaks, asking for help, or systematically testing solutions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to share problem-solving strategies like staying patient, asking for help, or breaking tasks into steps. Help them see that challenges are normal and effective strategies make problem-solving easier, such as retrying steps or taking breaks."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "07fa57ac-06b4-4672-b6b2-dc2cc8b14be5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7cd70e61-05a1-4e9d-bc20-8e72e09c8986"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf01d3e8-73e0-4960-9226-d1724922f85e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf01d3e8-73e0-4960-9226-d1724922f85e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7cd70e61-05a1-4e9d-bc20-8e72e09c8986"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22f260be-227e-4ae3-be29-689720c676c2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define the term *debugging*. Explain that there are processes and strategies that can be applied to identify the bugs and fix them.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students seem unsure, share a quick example of a real-world debugging process, like figuring out why a light bulb won’t turn on (e.g., checking the bulb, switch, or power source)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22f260be-227e-4ae3-be29-689720c676c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7cd70e61-05a1-4e9d-bc20-8e72e09c8986"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e93506d-1b21-4c33-8f9c-0f4ae2441f1d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e93506d-1b21-4c33-8f9c-0f4ae2441f1d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7cd70e61-05a1-4e9d-bc20-8e72e09c8986"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8aabc34-4c67-419c-b67e-14a36d5036fc",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8aabc34-4c67-419c-b67e-14a36d5036fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7cd70e61-05a1-4e9d-bc20-8e72e09c8986"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "228a9ec9-075f-4cda-9492-97cbdb43b22c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students in pairs. Give students a couple of minutes to review and discuss the displayed code with their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for students discussing potential errors such as: calling the function on a painter object that is incorrectly named and typos in the function calls.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that there are no wrong answers—this is about making educated guesses and practicing debugging mindsets. If students are stuck, ask guiding questions such as, “How does Python know which object to use when defining or calling a function?\" or \"Do the function names match exactly between the definition and the call?\" Encourage students to think like a detective by looking for clues in the code. If needed, remind them to focus on syntax and logical steps in the program."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "228a9ec9-075f-4cda-9492-97cbdb43b22c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f210db4-756e-4598-9769-4818e356c9bd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f210db4-756e-4598-9769-4818e356c9bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "183823de-3948-44b0-8632-06ac83968b58",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What bug did you find and how? Why might it be a bug? How could the bug be fixed?*\n- Ask for volunteers to share the bugs they identified in the code, how they found it, and their reasoning that it is an error.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize potential bugs such as calling a function with a name that doesn’t match its definition (typos in `move_adn_paint()` and `move_paint()`), as well as attempting to use a function that references a `Painter` object that was created with a different name (`sally`).",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students hesitate to share, remind them that debugging is about reasoning through errors, not just finding the \"right\" answer. Encourage them to find strategies that will work for debugging any code, such as reading over the function and variable names. If they struggle to identify the bugs, prompt them with guiding questions like:\n- Did you read the code line by line? \n- Does every function call match exactly with the function name in the definition?\n- Which object does the function reference? Has that object named painter actually been created?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "183823de-3948-44b0-8632-06ac83968b58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dcd17280-72c9-4402-a124-fea4520511bf",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dcd17280-72c9-4402-a124-fea4520511bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "991aa9b0-70cb-4f90-8710-2536ac71500e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to highlight the errors in the code and discuss how each bug can be fixed. Emphasize that sometimes there is more than one way to fix a bug, and debugging is about finding the best solution for the given situation. Relate the corrections back to student predictions to validate their reasoning.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Highlight how debugging involves looking for small details, like function names, as well as logical issues, like order of operations or painting twice without moving in between. Explain that there are often multiple ways to fix a bug, and part of debugging is choosing the best approach for the situation. For example, the `Painter` object error can be fixed either by changing the object name to match what’s in the the function or by modifying the function to use `painter` as a parameter and calling the function with the argument sally. Encourage students to explore different solutions and consider which is the most efficient or appropriate, which mirrors real-world debugging practices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "991aa9b0-70cb-4f90-8710-2536ac71500e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "539e7edf-9e54-4517-a480-a8f63826a852",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "539e7edf-9e54-4517-a480-a8f63826a852",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b48de9eb-e4e6-49c5-8c4b-07027e5acf60",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the four debugging strategies. Highlight how Validation Feedback should be done on each level that has validation tests and that it helps identify issues (e.g., outputs or behaviors that don’t match expectations) and serves as a starting point to apply the other strategies, such as tracing code or asking an AI assistant.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Introduction to Debugging Strategies",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that debugging is iterative and highlight how validation feedback leads to refinement, not just immediate fixes."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b48de9eb-e4e6-49c5-8c4b-07027e5acf60",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71aa6471-47db-47e3-a4b1-906da67093de",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71aa6471-47db-47e3-a4b1-906da67093de",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed49016f-bd81-42c8-baca-cc627e1ba019",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that error messages can be overwhelming at first. Use the example on the slide to help students understand how to read them step by step.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "We're focusing on an example for error messages because they can be confusing to read at first. The other debugging strategies—validation feedback, code tracing, and AI assistance—are more intuitive, so students will explore those through practice instead of a step-by-step example."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed49016f-bd81-42c8-baca-cc627e1ba019",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f26804e-a0c9-466a-9fdd-9115614401ce",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f26804e-a0c9-466a-9fdd-9115614401ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6cb13cb-fcd7-48d1-8e46-bc1a0f8e207a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Debugging Strategies handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There is a lot of information in this resource. Encourage students to read each section as they are working on that debugging strategy. For example, have them wait to read the section on using AI as a debugging tool until they reach the level that tells them to use the AI chatbot."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6cb13cb-fcd7-48d1-8e46-bc1a0f8e207a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62810cb3-2d1e-494c-a99a-f00468875ae8",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62810cb3-2d1e-494c-a99a-f00468875ae8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b701b73b-8a0c-4cf9-9bbc-0b51b1b482df",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students in pairs for pair programming. Make sure students are aware that for Levels 2 and 3, one student should be on the Investigate and Modify level while the other will be on Level 4 using the AI Chatbot.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 3 with their partner.\n- **Level 1:** Use code tracing and printing values to debug the error.\n- **Level 2:** Use the error message clarification strategy (and AI Chatbot on Level 4) to debug the error.\n- **Level 3:** Ask questions with the AI Chatbot on Level 4 on to help you understand the errors.\n- **Level 4:** AI Chatbot exists on this level for students to use with the debugging strategies on Levels 2 and 3.\n- **Level 5:** Students complete a Check for Understanding.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The discussions with the AI Chatbot on Level 4 do not save, so students will not be able to toggle back and forth between Levels to interact with the tool as they debug. To help with this issue, students should utilize pair programming. One student should have the programming level open on their device while their partner has the AI Chatbot level open on their device.\n \nStudents should be practicing using the validation feedback on all levels to help them test."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b701b73b-8a0c-4cf9-9bbc-0b51b1b482df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24eb6735-6fa9-4509-8358-371c2beb18b8",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24eb6735-6fa9-4509-8358-371c2beb18b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a324170e-4c08-4097-a61c-1d61e031b078",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered about the strategies from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain what a syntax error is and use the slide to go over a couple examples.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain what a logic error is and use the slide to show an example where the function would run without crashing, but it moves before painting instead of painting first, which is a logic error because the code runs but doesn’t do what was expected."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a324170e-4c08-4097-a61c-1d61e031b078",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ff4975d-72ac-4025-ae83-5d86ed7b49be",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 6 to complete at least one of the debugging practice choices.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Debugging Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ff4975d-72ac-4025-ae83-5d86ed7b49be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db8fb2cd-0bbb-47db-8a88-e2e298a2dc09",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the practice level, remind them to document their experiences in their Unit Guide and to consult their Debugging Strategies Handout or the AI Chatbot if needed. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, students can complete more than one debugging practice challenge choice level."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These levels assess the following learning objectives:\n- Apply debugging strategies such as code tracing, error message interpretation, and AI assistance to identify and resolve errors in code\n- Compare the effectiveness of different debugging strategies"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db8fb2cd-0bbb-47db-8a88-e2e298a2dc09",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c411a20f-f57a-4e84-b657-f9257759c94f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63135faf-241b-4a7d-b792-1ba229f0b952",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share one debugging strategy they found most useful and why before individually writing their own response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on each other’s ideas instead of just repeating the same answer. When writing their individual responses in the Unit Guide, students should include at least one specific example from today’s debugging practice."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses all three objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- Debugging as an iterative process (Objective 1)\n- Specific strategies used to debug their code (Objective 2)\n- A comparison of debugging strategies and their effectiveness (Objective 3)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63135faf-241b-4a7d-b792-1ba229f0b952",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b2c6635-0499-4964-a1e2-cf45429da714"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "844d3f89-2e6e-4e59-9c02-8d4b68fe202d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before students arrive, scatter small items (e.g., markers, paper clips, sticky notes) around the room and designate a cardboard box or plastic bin as the place for the items to end up. Tell students to read the prompt on the screen and follow the directions. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What was the condition for repeating the task?*\n- *What made the task stop?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that the condition was “items on the floor”. While this was still true, students needed to continue picking up the items and placing them in the bin. They stopped the task when all of the items had been collected.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *loop*. Give an example of activities that loop in real life, such as waking up for school, brushing your teeth, and following a school block period schedule.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "844d3f89-2e6e-4e59-9c02-8d4b68fe202d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0cbda043-6aea-4b7f-b9a0-13658951e3ea"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2fae2a7c-1e29-49e2-a672-a7fd548996e6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is an algorithm?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should remember that an algorithm is a list of steps. They should be able to reference the terms sequencing, selection, and iteration.*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the definition of an algorithm. Make sure students understand the definitions for sequencing and iteration before moving onto the code on the next slide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Does this algorithm contain sequencing, selection, and/or iteration?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check if students can identify both of these parts of an algorithm. If students are stuck, ask guiding questions like, \"What would happen if we changed the order of line 6 and 7?\" or \"Where do you see repetition in the code?\" \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** When programming in The Neighborhood, students need to be specific about the order of instructions to achieve their goal. This order is called sequencing. Students should be able to explain that they have to tell the `Painter` what to do step by step, like turn, move, paint.\n\nStudents have also encountered repeated code, or iteration, such as in lines 1-4, where the `Painter` is told to move and paint several times in a row. Iteration lets us repeat these steps without writing the same lines of code over and over. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Algorithms and Iteration"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2fae2a7c-1e29-49e2-a672-a7fd548996e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26a77a1e-89e3-4465-a926-97b96b583e39",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 1 on Code Studio to write their prediction for the program's outcome, then have students run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Predict"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26a77a1e-89e3-4465-a926-97b96b583e39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65a2ec89-fcb6-483e-9d2a-6bd33f350048",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about the code in this program? What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight student responses that mention the new `while` keyword. Ask students what they think the “while” loop is checking for, then ask what code will run next.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that this is a `while` loop. It checks if the condition `painter.can_move()` to the east before executing the lines of code inside: `painter.move()` and `painter.paint(“yellow”)`. The `Painter` keeps painting and moving while the condition is true. Once the condition is false, i.e. when the `Painter` can no longer move east, the loops stops and the program moves to the next instructions in the sequence: `turn_left()`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allowing students to look at the code in pairs can help them synthesize what they are learning by articulating their thoughts to each other, and hearing multiple perspectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65a2ec89-fcb6-483e-9d2a-6bd33f350048",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db0e397f-ad21-4319-bce4-91cfcb41ae39",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db0e397f-ad21-4319-bce4-91cfcb41ae39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63c20cb2-b258-441b-88d2-59609ed811da",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the steps for coding a `while` loop. Emphasize that a `while` loop simplifies repeated code and makes the program more efficient. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 2 to complete Levels 2 through 5.\n- **Level 2:** Students define a new `move_and_paint()` function which contains a `while painter.can_move()` loop.\n- **Level 3:** Refactor repetitive code into a `while painter.is_on_bucket()` loop inside a `collect_paint()` function.\n- **Level 4:** Refactor repetitive code into a `while painter.has_paint()` loop inside a `paint_line()` function.\n- **Level 5:** Check for understanding multiple choice question",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Investigate and Modify"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63c20cb2-b258-441b-88d2-59609ed811da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b0d6e59-d27a-4774-91cf-c6ca8ac52637",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete these levels will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objectives:\n- Explain the purpose and functionality of a `while` loop\n- Write `while` loops to repeat code while a condition is true\n- Use functions to encapsulate and reuse logic within `while` loops"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b0d6e59-d27a-4774-91cf-c6ca8ac52637",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73ff447a-ceeb-4921-9c54-2c51bba44f3e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73ff447a-ceeb-4921-9c54-2c51bba44f3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "532735e0-2307-4065-a5c9-1308b9d798fa",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you discover from the modifications you made to the code?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that pattern recognition, a crucial step in computational thinking, involves iteration. By finding repeated actions in their code, students were able to group repetitive steps into a loop instead of writing out the same code over and over. The loop knows to continue only as long as the condition is true, which means that students can use built-in methods to set the condition, such as `painter.can_move()` or `painter.is_on_bucket()`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the purpose of the `while` keyword.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the purpose of the *boolean condition*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "532735e0-2307-4065-a5c9-1308b9d798fa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1c70ee0-570d-4e11-af7e-fce6ea9289e9",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 6 to complete one of the challenges.**",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1c70ee0-570d-4e11-af7e-fce6ea9289e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ceefb0d9-dd59-427c-8ad9-a26646d0e1c9",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the practice level, remind them to use the code in their backpack from previous levels if necessary. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, students can complete more than one debugging practice challenge choice level."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These levels assess the following learning objectives:\n- The purpose and functionality of a `while` loop\n- `while` loops to repeat code while a condition is true\n- Functions to encapsulate and reuse logic within `while` loops"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ceefb0d9-dd59-427c-8ad9-a26646d0e1c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2eef6a09-2f62-422d-994b-4e6d38d37c75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8864392-350d-402c-93b7-0bb7ba0e5e5f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their Unit Guide. Then have students share their answer with a partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that while loops let you repeat a block of code as long as a condition is true. By placing a loop inside a function you can group tasks more efficiently and call the function whenever needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use examples from the levels they worked on to answer the question. Have them reference specific loops and functions they created in their programs."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8864392-350d-402c-93b7-0bb7ba0e5e5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2f4e5f49-b73b-4d0e-bd56-1e928e24b6d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "60f9757b-081c-4a24-9bcb-88911209f1e0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the instructions of the quick selection game. Students will listen to a description you give and then stand if it fits them. Pause and Discuss after each instruction and ask a student who didn’t stand to explain why. Here are a few descriptions to get the game started. “If you are wearing black, stand up.” “If you are wearing jewelry, stand up.” “If your name begins with the letter M or J.” ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each class will most likely use different conditions due to the uniqueness and variety of students, dress codes, etc. So, here are a few suggestions but you will may need to change these based on the makeup of your unique class and students. You can also change the conditions with each instruction and add more instructions in order to involve more students and if you have time."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "60f9757b-081c-4a24-9bcb-88911209f1e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d2bd87f-0b2a-4a55-8165-d4bbd652f979"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd521648-5213-4a70-910a-4dc3b812145e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd521648-5213-4a70-910a-4dc3b812145e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d2bd87f-0b2a-4a55-8165-d4bbd652f979"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "779fbe11-4bf8-4ea4-970a-97f905f410ab",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the definition and components of an algorithm. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which component of an algorithm did you just experience when you either stood or stayed seated?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should realize that they demonstrate selection.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that algorithms use sequencing, iteration, and selection. So far, we’ve explored sequencing (step-by-step) and iteration (repeating tasks). Today, we’ll focus on **selection**, where a program makes decisions using conditions. In Python, we use **if statements** for selection—let’s see how this works with our `Painter`!\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Share the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "779fbe11-4bf8-4ea4-970a-97f905f410ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d2bd87f-0b2a-4a55-8165-d4bbd652f979"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f97738c8-a07a-4825-a86c-595f8077bd4b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a moment to think about what the program will do. Allow students to discuss their predictions with a partner. Then have a few students share their predictions.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let the students know that they can assume a Painter object has been created called “painter” and that it has taken paint from the bucket. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f97738c8-a07a-4825-a86c-595f8077bd4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "abeb0d14-2f82-4c5c-be8a-303aaf509dd8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "abeb0d14-2f82-4c5c-be8a-303aaf509dd8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c60b7f98-1d98-466d-8125-e813a881cc77",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students view the GIF of the painter. Then have them compare what they predicted would happen to what they see happening on screen. If their prediction differed from the actual output, ask them to reflect on why that is.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Investigate and Modify",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should notice that the program contains two identical `if` statements. Both `if` statements check if the `Painter` can move south, but only the first one evaluates to `True`. This is because once the `Painter` takes a step forward it can no longer move south. As a result, the second `if` statement evaluates to `False` and that entire chunk of code is skipped.\n\nStudents might wonder why the second `if` statement doesn’t have any effect, whether the `Painter`’s position affects how conditionals work, or if the `Painter `is allowed to move south more than once. They might also question how `can_move(\"south\")` determines when movement is possible. Guide students to understand how the `can_move(direction)` checks for whether or not the `Painter` *could move* in that direction, rather than a command *to move* in that direction. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c60b7f98-1d98-466d-8125-e813a881cc77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6079dc44-cf2e-4e21-8b42-1b64e1e0027f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6079dc44-cf2e-4e21-8b42-1b64e1e0027f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "42877ee2-9f2c-4f04-b348-e0884f22c5e0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that conditionals *allow programs to make decisions* by checking if something is true before running certain code. Explain that methods like `can_move()` help check conditions *before executing actions* by returning a boolean, true or false. Code inside the `if` statement only runs if the condition is true—otherwise, it is skipped.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 5.\n- **Level 1:** Students explore how `can_move()` and function parameters can control movement and painting decisions. \n- **Level 2:** Students use `is_on_paint()` and `can_move()` inside conditionals to modify the `Painter`’s behavior.\n- **Level 3:** Students complete missing `if` statements** to control movement and painting based on the `Painter`’s facing direction.\n- **Level 4:** Students implement nested `if` statements to paint a diagonal pattern while controlling movement.\n- **Level 5:** Students complete a check for understanding."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "42877ee2-9f2c-4f04-b348-e0884f22c5e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63021d53-b123-41b4-a120-e4e04fa6b378",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Support students' transition from planning to coding while fostering independence and problem-solving skills by asking guiding questions when they get stuck.\n- “Python is picky about spaces and spelling—double-check your line.”\n- Encourage debugging: “What part of your code is working? What part isn’t? How can you figure out why?”\n- Highlight different strategies: “I like how you broke down this turn step.”\n- Suggest partnerships: “Check with your partner.”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63021d53-b123-41b4-a120-e4e04fa6b378",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a435cb6b-9fd3-4751-96aa-269a559cfc9f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a435cb6b-9fd3-4751-96aa-269a559cfc9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9c7d72b-4480-4319-bb75-96d2227c3794",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code. Do a quick whip around to allow students to share one thing they discovered or ask students to \"Raise a Righteous Hand\" to volunteer to share.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The protocol \"Raise a Righteous Hand\" involves students raising their hands to volunteer information, share experiences, or answer questions based on their unique knowledge or personal experiences. The term \"righteous\" in this context is used to emphasize the value and importance of the information being shared. It suggests that the contributions are genuine, meaningful, and worthy of attention and respect.\n\nPrompt students to share what they discovered about the following aspects:\n- Creating a conditional\n- Syntax for a conditional\n- `Painter` methods used with conditionals"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9c7d72b-4480-4319-bb75-96d2227c3794",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "edc5ce32-5ef1-4b34-8ec7-a1fcc806b726",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "edc5ce32-5ef1-4b34-8ec7-a1fcc806b726",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f40a038-e0dd-47ae-a0a2-711066e0664d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce *conditional statement*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the syntax for conditional statements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that conditionals allow programs to make decisions by checking if something is true before running certain code. Explain that methods like `can_move()` help check conditions before executing actions by returning a boolean, true or false. Code inside the `if` statement only runs if the condition is true—otherwise, it is skipped.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `Painter` methods students can use with conditional statements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 6 to practice using conditionals.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete these levels will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objectives:\n- Implementing basic conditional statements using `if` in Python.\n- Designing programs that make decisions using if statements"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f40a038-e0dd-47ae-a0a2-711066e0664d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc9bdf12-17b6-4bc8-b2b7-00baa23c51f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "215e4c13-50bd-4c62-b77e-d8203e7365bf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to individually answer the question of the day in their unit guide. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Answers to the question of the day can be used to formatively assess the following lesson objectives:\n- Implement basic conditional statements using `if` in Python.\n- Design programs that make decisions using if statements.\n\nLook for student answers to include that by using conditional statements, you can check if certain conditions are true and then run specific code based on that so that programs can react to different situations."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "215e4c13-50bd-4c62-b77e-d8203e7365bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc9cf60b-01a3-45a1-a6ac-eda8a194d1a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dafb97b3-8b59-4e1a-b4bd-08735fddb11b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dafb97b3-8b59-4e1a-b4bd-08735fddb11b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc9cf60b-01a3-45a1-a6ac-eda8a194d1a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c5543ac3-20f4-45d3-b32a-3110ea296ab9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that today we used `if` statements to help the `Painter` make decisions, like whether to move, paint, or take paint based on specific conditions. In real life, programs often make similar decisions based on conditions. For example, a program might decide who gets a scholarship, a loan or a job based on certain criteria.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Use the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *What happens if the conditions for making these decisions are unfair, biased, or incomplete?*\n- *How could someone ensure the conditions used in a program are fair and don’t exclude or harm certain groups?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the conditions used in a program determine its decisions and can impact fairness. The goal is for students to consider how biased or incomplete conditions could lead to unintended harm and discuss ways to make conditions more inclusive, such as testing on diverse groups or considering different perspectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that when we wrote `if` statements today, we controlled what the `Painter` did based on specific conditions, like whether it could move or was on paint. In programming, those conditions might be simple, but in real-world applications, the conditions can affect people’s lives. As programmers, it is important to think critically about the logic we write and the conditions we choose.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c5543ac3-20f4-45d3-b32a-3110ea296ab9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc9cf60b-01a3-45a1-a6ac-eda8a194d1a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1bd5e9c-b4cb-44d7-a258-c9990141a574",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1bd5e9c-b4cb-44d7-a258-c9990141a574",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c9782db-cd47-4819-a97a-ac5a1ee5ada0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74b01e30-e109-4531-a786-617baed73743",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What apps do you use every day?*\n- *What kind of general algorithms do they use to solve problems for you?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that many apps rely on algorithms to solve problems and make decisions, often without users realizing it. They should begin making connections between common apps and the types of algorithms they use, such as recommendation systems, search ranking, and navigation. Listen for examples that show an understanding of how algorithms influence daily experiences, such as streaming services suggesting content, navigation apps calculating routes, or shopping apps recommending products.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that they have been writing algorithms to navigate our Painter around the Neighborhood, but today, they are going to explore how algorithms work in real-world apps and how their design can impact users like you and me.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74b01e30-e109-4531-a786-617baed73743",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c9782db-cd47-4819-a97a-ac5a1ee5ada0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bfc90c2c-2637-46d0-9ac1-c11ca219cead",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students the Algorithm Decision-Making activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 1 of their activity guide where they analyze a flawed music selection algorithm using a flowchart, identify what the algorithm currently does, its limitations, and possible improvements. Guide them to focus on how the algorithm makes recommendations and whether it considers diverse user preferences. Clarify that this is an analysis activity, not about finding a single correct answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, listen for discussions identifying the algorithm’s behavior, such as only recommending songs from the first selected genre. Look for students recognizing limitations like lack of diversity or bias toward initial choices. Encourage creative improvement ideas, such as incorporating recent searches or expanding recommendations over time. ",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Debugging a Music Selection Algorithm",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage them to think critically about how the algorithm makes decisions and how it could be more effective. Emphasize that there are no wrong answers—the goal is to develop problem-solving skills and consider the broader impact of algorithmic choices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bfc90c2c-2637-46d0-9ac1-c11ca219cead",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20f8ba50-afc7-4486-9283-6d917ffe483f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20f8ba50-afc7-4486-9283-6d917ffe483f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a623d3b9-6481-4c0e-b89d-c3ca4e9c53a8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the Give One, Get One activity and direct students to participate in a Give One, Get One to share their ideas for proposed solutions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity. Click the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue.\n\nGive One, Get One encourages students to seek and share ideas and information. Students circulate the classroom and pair up with a partner when prompted by the teacher. Each student \"gives\" or shares one of their ideas as the other student \"gets\" or listens and writes it down. The teacher then prompts students to find new partners and repeat the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a623d3b9-6481-4c0e-b89d-c3ca4e9c53a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f70fbada-a7ed-4123-a499-ece6141e8d3a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f70fbada-a7ed-4123-a499-ece6141e8d3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e561674-589f-4cc2-9723-a47cc094aecf",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What similarities do you see across these suggestions?*\n- *What challenges might arise when implementing these improvements?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize common themes in their proposed improvements, such as increasing variety in recommendations or considering user feedback. They should also discuss challenges like balancing personalization with diversity or ensuring the algorithm adapts over time. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e561674-589f-4cc2-9723-a47cc094aecf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24387f7b-196f-4a67-9dc6-d78520b3cac3",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *bias*. Have students add an example, an image, or a connection that would help them makes sense of the work in their unit guide.  \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *ethics*. Have students add an example, an image, or a connection that would help them makes sense of the work in their unit guide.  \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 2 of their activity guide where they analyze the self-driving car decision-making algorithm by identifying what it does, the factors it considers, the trade-offs involved, and who benefits or is harmed. Encourage them to think critically about the algorithm’s priorities and limitations. Remind them that real-world algorithms must balance multiple factors, often leading to ethical dilemmas.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, listen for discussions identifying the algorithm’s steps, such as detecting obstacles, assessing risks, and making a decision. Look for students recognizing the factors considered, like pedestrian safety, passenger safety, and legal concerns. Encourage analysis of trade-offs, such as whether avoiding one accident increases the risk of another. Pay attention to conversations about ethical implications, including who benefits, who is at risk, and what makes a decision \"fair.\" ",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Ethical Exploration of Autonomous Vehicle Algorithms",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, consider showing the Waymo Self-Driving gif located in the Teacher Resources to demonstrate a real-life autonomous vehicle swerving to avoid a pedestrian. Use this example to highlight how real-world AI must make split-second ethical decisions and how different scenarios could lead to different outcomes.\n\nThroughout this part of the activity, ask guiding questions like, “What criteria does the car prioritize? What factors are missing?” to deepen student thinking. Encourage discussion among partners by prompting students to consider whether there is a \"right\" decision or if it depends on the situation. Connect the discussion to real-world AI challenges, highlighting how autonomous vehicles must make split-second ethical decisions with real consequences."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24387f7b-196f-4a67-9dc6-d78520b3cac3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9940350-90de-41ec-8d0d-6b5cf843b46b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9940350-90de-41ec-8d0d-6b5cf843b46b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "80a9a45a-a340-49b6-b1c5-3a4e0bd38867",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What challenges arise when designing algorithms that make critical decisions affecting people’s lives?*\n- *How does public trust in autonomous systems depend on ethical decision-making?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the challenges of designing decision-making algorithms that balance fairness, ethics, and functionality, and how these challenges impact public trust in autonomous systems. Listen for students identifying trade-offs in algorithmic decisions, such as prioritizing safety vs. efficiency, and discussing how bias, transparency, or accountability affect trust in AI systems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to consider multiple perspectives by asking follow-up questions like, \"Who benefits from this decision? Who might be harmed?\" or \"How would you feel if you were affected by this algorithm?\" If students focus only on technical challenges, prompt them to think about ethics and public trust by asking, \"Would people trust a system that makes decisions without transparency?\" Remind students that there are no perfect answers—the goal is to explore trade-offs in algorithmic decision-making."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Activity guides can be collected and used to formatively assess the objectives:\n- Analyze the role of algorithms in apps to solve real-world problems.\n- Debug an algorithm and propose changes to improve functionality for diverse users.\n- Evaluate ethical implications of algorithmic decision-making."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "80a9a45a-a340-49b6-b1c5-3a4e0bd38867",
        "lesson_activity.key": "beef1898-63bf-4b9d-9d04-aef03869f6aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "08f0b1bf-58ff-4130-8023-d07aef17134d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to write their responses to the question of the day in their Unit Guide. After a moment, click the slide to display a helpful hint for how students can think about this question in the context of their experiences today. After 2–3 minutes, facilitate a quick sharing activity (e.g., Whip Around or Popcorn Share), calling on a few students to share their ideas.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives. Look for depth of understanding in how students connect algorithmic decision-making to real-world impact and ethical considerations. Specifically, they should check for:\n- **Examples of how algorithms impact daily life** – Does the student mention real-world applications like recommendation systems, self-driving cars, or hiring algorithms?\n- **Recognition of ethical challenges** – Does the student acknowledge issues like bias, fairness, or unintended consequences in algorithm design?\n- **Consideration of trade-offs** – Does the student discuss how programmers must balance accuracy, efficiency, and ethical responsibility when designing algorithms?\n- **A thoughtful perspective on responsible algorithm design** – Does the student suggest ways to make algorithms more fair, transparent, or trustworthy?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "08f0b1bf-58ff-4130-8023-d07aef17134d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dcb8ecbf-25d3-4b74-a32f-33e4af9ff15d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bb9a1095-bbc7-4be5-a2e0-68c0958347a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that earlier in the unit, they explored the pillars of computational thinking—Decomposition, Pattern Recognition, Abstraction, and Algorithm Design—to solve programming challenges. Explain that today's lesson focuses on decomposition, breaking a problem into smaller steps to make it easier to solve. Ask students what they remember about these pillars and encourage them to share examples of when they used them in previous lessons. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How have you used decomposition - breaking problems down into smaller steps - throughout your work in this unit or outside of school?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize how decomposition helps break down complex tasks into smaller, more manageable steps, both in programming and everyday problem-solving. Listen for responses that describe breaking tasks into steps, such as planning a coding project, organizing a school assignment, or learning a new skill.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bb9a1095-bbc7-4be5-a2e0-68c0958347a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78786bbf-01b6-468f-a20c-2d44a4c63035"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cadb1efd-fd50-45e0-adf0-5316bf448cff",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Decomposing a Pixel Image activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk students through the tasks in their activity guide. Explain that they will first choose a pixel image to recreate, then identify patterns and define functions to break the image into smaller, manageable pieces. Next, they will write pseudocode to describe how they will code the image before sharing their plan with another group for T.A.G. feedback (Tell, Ask, Give). Encourage students to focus on decomposition and efficiency as they plan. Leave this slide up while students work so they can refer back to the steps.",
        "name": "Decomposing a Pixel Image",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The images are presented in order from easiest (top left) to most difficult (bottom right). If students are struggling to pick an image to discuss with their partner, consider guiding them to choose an image based on difficulty-level."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cadb1efd-fd50-45e0-adf0-5316bf448cff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6cd43ca1-76b1-46a7-b69d-10d2fd20bf66",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6cd43ca1-76b1-46a7-b69d-10d2fd20bf66",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79d5d1f5-f941-4d13-b35f-e2d92479808b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the visual for the TAG feedback protocol. Remind them that their job is to Tell the group something they like about their code, Ask a question about the code, and Give a suggestion for improvement. Encourage them to focus on clarity, efficiency, and organization in the pseudocode.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students aren’t expected to finish coding their entire image in the allotted time. Encourage them to do the TAG protocol even if they have only just started coding. This will give them a valuable opportunity to receive feedback from peers and articulate their next steps for coding their projects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79d5d1f5-f941-4d13-b35f-e2d92479808b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f664894f-ccfb-4e7c-bcb8-422270be30a5",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f664894f-ccfb-4e7c-bcb8-422270be30a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c975fa70-0dac-4b14-b914-74f0db8fb2f0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that in this activity, the focus is on designing algorithms to recreate a pixel image, rather than collecting paint. Since the exact amount of paint needed is unknown, there are no paint buckets in this level. Instead, students will use `painter.set_paint(amount)` to set the amount of paint directly in their programs, ensuring they have enough to complete their image efficiently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 1 to convert their pseudocode into Python and create their pixel image."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c975fa70-0dac-4b14-b914-74f0db8fb2f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2912f079-7fa6-4904-9cec-8ca88dbeafa8",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, check that they are defining and calling functions correctly and using consistent function names. Listen for debugging discussions and prompt students to compare their code to their pseudocode when they get stuck. Encourage them to test in small steps instead of writing everything at once.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Depending on the timing of the lesson, you can allot more time for students to finish coding their pixel images or allow them to click “Remix” on the level to create additional images.\n\nIf students struggle with debugging, ask guiding questions like, “What part of your code is working? What’s not?” or “How does this compare to your pseudocode?” Encourage them to use print statements to check their logic and troubleshoot errors."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The activity guide and Level 1 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Breaking down a complex problem into smaller, manageable parts using decomposition\n- Writing and revising pseudocode based on peer feedback before coding their image\n- Defining and calling functions to code an image"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2912f079-7fa6-4904-9cec-8ca88dbeafa8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "164f4c24-3523-4c48-a7a2-f68eb5df2d1c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17450fec-88ae-467e-ab41-eb50ec7fb707",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students answer today’s Question of the Day by ranking themselves on the scales in their Unit Guide. Encourage them to reflect on their approach to problem-solving, collaboration, and focus while coding their pixel image.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check in with students who seem unsure how to rank themselves. Ask guiding questions like, \"Did you follow a structured plan or experiment with new ideas?\" or \"Did you work through challenges independently or with a partner?\" Encourage them to use the scale to self-assess their coding process.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students reference specific functions they created in their programs when justifying their rankings. If time allows, ask a few students to share how their choices helped them break down and code the image efficiently."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day responses in the unit guide provide insight into how well students understand decomposition and their ability to apply it effectively in coding."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17450fec-88ae-467e-ab41-eb50ec7fb707",
        "lesson_activity.key": "69222aae-c66d-4986-ab3b-865a9c46def8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ccff7d76-7227-462e-b247-7c479fae712f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ccff7d76-7227-462e-b247-7c479fae712f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "69222aae-c66d-4986-ab3b-865a9c46def8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3fb0b320-e0c7-415a-a2b8-345381a2a22c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students pair up and share how they rated themselves on the scales in their Unit Guide. Encourage them to discuss which characteristic helped them the most and whether their approach was different from their partner’s.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for students discussing how their problem-solving, collaboration, or focus impacted their coding process. Encourage them to provide specific examples from their work. If students struggle to compare approaches, ask guiding questions like, “Did you focus more on structure or creativity?” or “How did working independently or collaboratively affect your efficiency?”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to reflect on how different approaches can be equally effective in problem-solving. If time allows, invite a few pairs to share their insights with the class to highlight the variety of approaches used."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3fb0b320-e0c7-415a-a2b8-345381a2a22c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "69222aae-c66d-4986-ab3b-865a9c46def8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9fb853c5-688a-4c39-bd97-545455436499",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Selection Flowchart activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Go through the flow of through the example and explain how the different results of the decision points change the path that is taken. Explain the what the different shapes represent (decision points and end points).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students come up with their own simple flowchart and fill out the decision points and end points with their partner on their activity guide. Then have students share and compare their flowcharts with another pair. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *two-way selection*. Give an example of activities that require making a decision, such as whether to go outside or not.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *nested conditional*. Give examples of activities that require making a decision based on a previous decision. For example, deciding first whether to go outside or stay inside and then if you go outside, deciding whether to ride your bike or play soccer with friends.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9fb853c5-688a-4c39-bd97-545455436499",
        "lesson_activity.key": "963a31a2-dae7-47b7-aff6-fd383ccbaf6b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d1ca628-8798-423c-9f4b-0bd5f88a19c2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 1 to write their prediction for the program's outcome Then have students run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Predict"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d1ca628-8798-423c-9f4b-0bd5f88a19c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68594fca-4313-494b-9178-2b26e53ee9a6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check if students correctly predicted that the program will make the Painter move forward and paint until it reaches an obstacle and then turns right, moves forward, and paints blue."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68594fca-4313-494b-9178-2b26e53ee9a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13fccf9a-0a3a-492e-b778-c1a4fbefdf28",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about the code in this program? What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students will notice that the program asks for a color and uses that input when the Painter paints a square. They might also notice that the Painter does different things based on its direction—if it faces west, it paints white and moves, but otherwise, it turns right before painting the chosen color. This might make them wonder what happens if the Painter does if facing west, how their color choice affects the outcome, or why the Painter turns before painting in some cases.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allowing students to look at the code in pairs can help them synthesize what they are learning by articulating their thoughts to each other, and hearing multiple perspectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13fccf9a-0a3a-492e-b778-c1a4fbefdf28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ac4fd24-80d0-4dfc-ba69-46f9d847aba0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ac4fd24-80d0-4dfc-ba69-46f9d847aba0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e694232f-b971-4032-82c2-7456dc8cccac",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to complete Lesson 12, Level 2 t complete Levels 2, 3, and 4.\n- **Level 2:** Students use user input to set the paint amount \n- **Level 3:** Students add a missing else statement to their conditional.\n- **Level 4:** Students modify the current conditional statement to be a nested conditional statement. ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Investigate and Modify"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e694232f-b971-4032-82c2-7456dc8cccac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5eb9aefd-414e-4d20-8279-28467e13a7cc",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to students collaborate with each other, providing support to those who are stuck. As students work through these levels, remind them to work with their partner to talk through questions and to seek clarifications. Students can also refer to the Python documentation to get more information about Python.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students who successfully complete these levels will have demonstrated mastery of the following lesson objectives:\n- Use `if/else` to choose between actions.\n- Nest conditionals for more outcomes.\n- Use input in a conditional statement."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5eb9aefd-414e-4d20-8279-28467e13a7cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24d592ca-a3ac-4771-8da2-664a562796fc",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24d592ca-a3ac-4771-8da2-664a562796fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a367df0e-652a-4998-bd53-99dfdbc17242",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students reflect on the value of taking in user input. They should be able to articulate that taking user input makes the program more interactive and customizable. Then have students reflect on how adding in nested conditionals, especially ones that rely on user input to determine the condition, lead to more possibilities for different outcomes and increased customization of the final drawing.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the animated slide to explain how an `if/else` conditional works. Highlight the fact that one of the blocks *will* run. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the animated slide to explain how a nested conditional works. While the example on the slide shows a conditional nested in the `if` block, point out the fact that a conditional can be nested in either the `if` block or the `else` block.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the animated slide to explain how an equality operator works. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 6 to complete one of the challenges.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a367df0e-652a-4998-bd53-99dfdbc17242",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43c96a56-4658-472c-986c-11ab6a6b14e2",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the practice level, remind them to use the code in their backpack from previous levels if necessary. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, students can complete more than one debugging practice challenge choice level."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These levels assess the following learning objectives:\n- Use `if/else` to choose between actions.\n- Nest conditionals for more outcomes.\n- Use input in a conditional statement."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43c96a56-4658-472c-986c-11ab6a6b14e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "30e69578-ae84-4815-ad62-e13f81010b87"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4e4059e-6d77-48a8-9aa5-f9d0711c0d2f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4e4059e-6d77-48a8-9aa5-f9d0711c0d2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6b6563e9-d10f-4b29-8ace-3b94dfd951aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b74af793-74c8-448c-9785-e4cf8ac6fde5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why would your feed look different from your friends?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Identify how nested conditionals shape personalized experiences in apps and apply that understanding to programming interactive features.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their Unit Guide. Then have students share their answer with a partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that they can make their programs more interactive by using two-way selection statements to make decisions based on conditions that the user inputs.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use examples from the levels they worked on to answer the question. Have them reference specific loops and functions they created in their programs."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b74af793-74c8-448c-9785-e4cf8ac6fde5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6b6563e9-d10f-4b29-8ace-3b94dfd951aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f93df463-8532-4f08-aeb9-8f5187151423",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Pixels of Me Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use the first box in their Planning Guide to brainstorm hobbies or interests they have and any careers that might be associated with them. Allow students to share their lists, idea webs, or sketches with an elbow partner as this may give them more ideas that they had not thought of themselves.  ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to come up with some hobbies they have both in and outside of school. The more they come up with, the more ideas they will have to choose from for their project pixel design. You can also prompt students to think about how their interests relate to their future career goals."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f93df463-8532-4f08-aeb9-8f5187151423",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f335a3b5-2d54-4de5-97a8-69b90eccc7df",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f335a3b5-2d54-4de5-97a8-69b90eccc7df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "346aecc9-ebc5-462e-b9b0-6fc246f83f1e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use the second box in their Planning Guide to brainstorm ideas for how they could represent any their ideas or interests visually. Again, allow students to share their ideas with a partner as this might give them more ideas beyond than what they had thought of themselves.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What skills have you learned in this unit that could help you create this pixel image?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain how they can use the Neighborhood grid, Painter object and Python code such as functions, loops, and conditionals to “paint” their image. They should also explain how they can use computational thinking skills (decomposition, pattern recognition, abstraction, and algorithms) as well as skills and characteristics such as creativity, problem-solving, team work, detail-oriented, and others discussed throughout the unit to create their algorithms.  "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "346aecc9-ebc5-462e-b9b0-6fc246f83f1e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e75a43fa-5883-4c4c-963c-6ec61751cba4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the first part of the project requirements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the remaining project requirements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the rubric on the last two pages of the project planning guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the project requirements and rubric? What does success look like for this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the components to implement in their program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e75a43fa-5883-4c4c-963c-6ec61751cba4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a118ae4-a347-4d7d-bddc-9bc9a8b938ad",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a118ae4-a347-4d7d-bddc-9bc9a8b938ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c92fe8a7-bcdc-4542-9d45-9d19a7505741",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 1 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 2 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 3 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Inform students that they will have the AI Chatbot on Level 2 to use for whatever support they need throughout the process. They can use AI to help them brainstorm, decompose their image, write pseudocode, or help debug any errors.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to sketch their pixels of me design, identify the repeated patterns in the image, the functions they should define to create those patterns, and write pseudocode for their functions to plan their project on the Pixels of Me Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students who might be struggling with any of the decomposition steps or with writing their pseudocode for their functions. Encourage students to use the AI chatbot if they need help getting started.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that the Pixels of Me design should be simple enough to create in the given timeframe while being complex enough to utilize the methods, user-defined functions with loops and conditionals. Students can use the AI chatbot to help them brainstorm different ideas for images they might use to represent their interests."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c92fe8a7-bcdc-4542-9d45-9d19a7505741",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e783db3-dbbb-4dbd-8f8d-a7de97478630",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e783db3-dbbb-4dbd-8f8d-a7de97478630",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf315139-39af-497a-b53e-6eb3cc95937a",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 1 to select the corresponding grid size that they selected in their project planning guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf315139-39af-497a-b53e-6eb3cc95937a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d9e12b3-a033-4b51-9d4a-d8d0274c3b80",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Encourage students to share and discuss their functions with a thought partner while working. As you move around the room, engage students with questions about their image, its repeated parts, the functions they plan on creating, and how they might use the AI chatbot."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d9e12b3-a033-4b51-9d4a-d8d0274c3b80",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3f70186-703e-4dda-81bc-e05b86b02039",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3f70186-703e-4dda-81bc-e05b86b02039",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "998634b1-2e91-498f-81c3-f8e3c35d3f20",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Day 1 Reflection section in their project planning guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing these reflection questions with a thought partner. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor and with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "998634b1-2e91-498f-81c3-f8e3c35d3f20",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9f2e9877-0824-40e4-8f58-3d99823b8727"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30c4a892-d4bc-4cb8-810e-5020dcf77679",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which function did you write first? Why?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain why they chose to start with writing the function they did. Perhaps they chose to start with that function because it was the quickest to test. Or perhaps they knew that it would hit the most rows in the rubric by utilizing various algorithmic concepts and organized code.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Keep this warm up quick and short in order to give students as much time as possible to program their image today."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30c4a892-d4bc-4cb8-810e-5020dcf77679",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7c135f4d-0621-4f11-a6cf-f5112f4a9252",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7c135f4d-0621-4f11-a6cf-f5112f4a9252",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96af3790-10a0-4388-add4-500e83653b2c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the tasks to complete for Day 2 of the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 1 to continue developing their projects.",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96af3790-10a0-4388-add4-500e83653b2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34ecab3e-a834-433b-8f7f-7a5428901431",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Remind students to comment their code with meaningful descriptions. As you move around the room, encourage students to test their functions incrementally (e.g., one function at a time). \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to TAG one to two peers' programs. As they have done previously, students will leave this TAG feedback on sticky notes at their peer’s computer. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be at different points when it is time for the TAG review. Emphasize to students that their work does not need to be completed to get feedback. Remind students that the problem-solving and development process is iterative and that receiving feedback from peers while they are working can help give them additional insights, perspectives, and guidance."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34ecab3e-a834-433b-8f7f-7a5428901431",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d858e38-dd78-40b1-99e6-99a9e4e4305e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d858e38-dd78-40b1-99e6-99a9e4e4305e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5c883df8-f50a-482e-9c03-6fcb52aa5705",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Day 2 Reflection section in their project planning guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing these reflection questions with a thought partner. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor and with the class."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "You can use the Day 2 Reflection as evidence for Reflection on AI and Peer Feedback rubric criteria."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5c883df8-f50a-482e-9c03-6fcb52aa5705",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bd6554c6-9cfd-4ab4-ac5d-e30a10876a2b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4d4da22-6311-4447-9b42-40757be06783",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *What are you most proud of about your project so far?*\n- *What challenges do you still need to overcome before submitting your project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they are proud of about their project and any challenges they still need to overcome before they submit their project. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, allow students to share with several people so they can share what they are proud of while hearing about other’s challenges to help them feel okay about their own challenges."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4d4da22-6311-4447-9b42-40757be06783",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4058170-389b-4a5e-b649-58cd6fdb025f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5bc01b81-e819-4e02-a0fd-4c6ee2cd4070",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5bc01b81-e819-4e02-a0fd-4c6ee2cd4070",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4058170-389b-4a5e-b649-58cd6fdb025f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00d72194-b7f1-477b-90e1-f69cb33be445",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the tasks to complete for Day 3 of the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students self-assess their project using the rubric on the Pixels of Me Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to finish developing their Pixels of Me projects.",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Activity"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00d72194-b7f1-477b-90e1-f69cb33be445",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4058170-389b-4a5e-b649-58cd6fdb025f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2e61400a-9f3b-4ed8-a7b9-0aa148265d14",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to use the feedback they received from their TAG review and self-assessment to finalize their Pixels of Me project. Have students submit their projects at the end of the allotted time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Remind students to comment their code with meaningful descriptions. Have students review their rubric and prioritize work on any rows where they do not yet show extensive evidence.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Distribute several sticky notes to each student for the gallery walk.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to participate in the Gallery Walk by displaying their project and then going around the room to view classmate’s projects and leave sticky notes with kudos, questions or observations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Move around the room to observe how students are engaging with the displayed projects. Encourage students to leave a note about what they find interesting or insightful about their peers' work. Prompt them to consider how the pixel images represent their classmates’ identities. Ensure that students are thoughtfully engaging with a variety of projects, not just those of their closest peers."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2e61400a-9f3b-4ed8-a7b9-0aa148265d14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4058170-389b-4a5e-b649-58cd6fdb025f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78499e6e-2a8c-4372-b265-d7d5f38312f7",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the End of Project Reflection section in their project planning guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing these reflection questions with a thought partner. ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor and with the class."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "You can use the Pixels of Me Planning Guide as evidence for the Computational Thinking in Planning rubric criteria. The End of Project Reflection as evidence for Reflection on AI and Peer Feedback rubric criteria."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78499e6e-2a8c-4372-b265-d7d5f38312f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4058170-389b-4a5e-b649-58cd6fdb025f"
      }
    }
  ],
